  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 7.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "- And they asked him, saying, Master, but when shall these things be? and what sign will there be when these things shall come to pass?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " St. Mark (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 13:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") tells us that these questioners were Peter and James, John and Andrew. They said to their Master, \"When shall these things be, and what sign shall precede them?\" They asked their question with mingled feelings of awe and gladness: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of awe",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for the ruin of their loved temple, and all that would probably accompany the catastrophe, was a dread thought; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of gladness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for they associated the fall of city and temple with the manifestation of their Lord in glory. In this glory they would assuredly share. But they wished to know more respecting the times and seasons of the dread event. Of late the disciples had begun dimly to see that no Messianic restoration such as they had been taught to expect was contemplated by their Master. They were recasting their hopes, and this solemn prediction they read in the light of the late sad and gloomy words which he had spoken of himself and his fortunes. Perhaps he would leave them for a season and then return, and, amid the crash of the ruined city and temple, set up his glorious kingdom. But they longed to know when this would be; hence the question of the four. The Lord's answer treated, in its first and longer portion, exclusively of the destruction of Jerusalem and its temple - the fair city and the glorious house on which they were then gazing, glorified in the light of the sunset splendor; then, as he spoke, gradually the horizon widened, and the Master touched upon the fortunes of  the great world lying beyond the narrow pale of the doomed, chosen people. He closes his grand summary of the world's fortunes By a sketch of his own return in glory. The disciples' hearts must have sunk as they listened; for how many ages lay Between ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "now",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "then!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Yet was the great prophecy full of comfort, and in later days was of inestimable practical value to the Jerusalem Christians. The discourse, which extends from ver. 8 to ver. 36, has been well divided by Godet into four divisions. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The apparent signs of the great catastrophe, which must not Be mistaken for true signs (vers. 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "-19). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The true sign, and the destruction of Jerusalem, which will immediately follow it, with the time of the Gentiles, which will be connected with it (vers. 20-24). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
